# Default Parameters

A **default parameter** gives a function a fallback value when the caller does not provide that argument:

```javascript
function greet(name, language = "English") {
    if (language === "Hindi") return `Namaste, ${name}!`;
    return `Hello, ${name}!`;
}

greet("Rahul");              // Hello, Rahul! — default used
greet("Priya", "Hindi");    // Namaste, Priya! — default overridden
```

Default parameters must come **after** required parameters.

## Rest Parameters

When you do not know how many arguments a caller will pass, use a **rest parameter** — it collects all extra arguments into an array:

```javascript
function sum(...numbers) {
    return numbers.reduce((total, n) => total + n, 0);
}

console.log(sum(1, 2, 3));           // 6
console.log(sum(10, 20, 30, 40));    // 100
```

The `...` syntax before the last parameter name turns it into a rest parameter. Only one rest parameter is allowed and it must be last.

## Returning Multiple Values

JavaScript functions can return only one value — but that value can be an **object** or **array** containing multiple pieces of data:

```javascript
function getStats(scores) {
    const total = scores.reduce((s, n) => s + n, 0);
    return {
        count:   scores.length,
        total,                       // shorthand: total: total
        average: total / scores.length,
        max:     Math.max(...scores),
        min:     Math.min(...scores),
    };
}

const stats = getStats([85, 92, 78, 95, 88]);
console.log(stats.average);  // 87.6
```

## Destructuring Return Values

You can unpack an object return value immediately:

```javascript
const { average, max, min } = getStats([85, 92, 78]);
console.log(average, max, min);
```

In the code example below, you will see default parameters, rest parameters, and an object return used in a statistics calculator.

